Nucleotide and deduced amino acid sequences were obtained and further analyzed. Following BLAST of the nucleotide sequence, the L1, L2, M1 and S3 segments of MPC/04 showed the highest nucleotide sequence identity (78.2–93.7%) with reovirus strain BYD1 (isolated from human), the M3, S1, S2 segments showed highest identities (95.2–97.9%) to MRV-HLJ/2007 (isolated from swine) (Fig. 3
). The MPC/04 S1 segment was clustered in the mammalian reovirus serotype 3 group and shared the highest identity with the porcine strains MRV-HLJ/2007, SC-A and GD-1 (nucleotide identities were 97.9%, 93.4% and 94.5%) (Fig. 4
). Phylogenetic analysis of MPC/04 showing that each segment was derived from an independent evolutionary path indicates that reassortment occurred during evolution.
